           <li type="disc" class="instruct_normal"><a href="#CAKE">Fire Truck Cake</a></li>
           <li type="disc" class="instruct_normal"><a href="#PBUTTER">Friends are Like Peanut Butter and Jelly</a></li>
           <li class="instruct_normal" type="disc"><a href="#SAND">Sand Dough</a><br></li>
          </ul>
          <p class="instruct_normal"><img src="images/separator_green2.gif" alt="separator" height="33" width="380" border="0"></p>
          <p class="grownups_title"><a name="EMP"></a><font color="#ed1c24">Empañadas</font></p>
          <p class="instruct_normal">An empañada is similar to a turnover. Empañadas are traditionally stuffed with fillings, such as meats and cheeses or fruit, and are then deep-fried. Adapt this traditional dish by baking the empañadas instead. Have each child press a plastic lid onto a pie crust sheet to cut out a circle. Place the circle on a cookie sheet sprayed with nonstick spray. Then place a heaping tablespoon of cooked, spiced ground meat and shredded cheese or fruit pie filling in the center of the circle. Fold the circle over and press the edges together to seal them. Bake the empañadas at 400° until lightly browned. Fruit-filled empañadas are great sprinkled with cinnamon sugar. Allow empañadas to cool before serving.</p>
          <p class="footer_nav"><a href="#TOP">top of page</a></p>
          <p class="instruct_normal"><img src="images/separator_green2.gif" alt="separator" height="33" width="380" border="0"></p>
          <p class="grownups_title"><a name="TOAST"></a><font color="#ed1c24">Toasted Pumpkin Seeds</font></p>
          <p class="instruct_normal">Wash seeds and spread out evenly on paper towels to dry. In a bowl, mix 2 Tbsp. melted butter, 1/2 tsp. Worcestershire sauce, and a dash of salt. Stir in pumpkin seeds and coat with mixture. Spread seeds on a baking sheet with an edge and toast for 1 hour at 250°.</p>
          <p class="footer_nav"><a href="#TOP">top of page</a></p>
          <p class="instruct_normal"><img src="images/separator_green2.gif" alt="separator" height="33" width="380" border="0"></p>
          <p class="grownups_title"><a name="PUMPPIE"></a><font color="#ed1c24">Frozen Pumpkin Pie</font></p>
          <p class="grownups_bold_blue">Prepared graham cracker crumb crust<br> 1 cup canned mashed pumpkin<br> 1/4 cup brown sugar, firmly packed<br> 4 cups low-fat vanilla ice cream or frozen yogurt, softened<br> 1/2 teaspoon salt<br> 1/2 teaspoon cinnamon<br> 1/2 teaspoon ginger<br> 1/4 teaspoon nutmeg<br> Raisins</p>
          <p class="instruct_normal">Mix pumpkin with brown sugar, salt, and spices. Fold in softened low-fat ice cream or frozen yogurt. Pour mixture into crust. For Halloween, arrange raisins on top to make a funny face. Freeze until firm.</p>
          <p class="footer_nav"><a href="#TOP">top of page</a></p>
          <p class="instruct_normal"><img src="images/separator_green2.gif" alt="separator" height="33" width="380" border="0"></p>
          <p class="grownups_title"><a name="SALAD"></a><font color="#ed1c24">Friendship Salad</font></p>
          <p class="instruct_normal">Have the children work together to create a friendship salad. Ahead of time, prepare fruits as needed (remove stems, peelings, etc.). Let the children wash the fruits and use blunt plastic knives to cut the fruit into small pieces. As they work, encourage the children to name the fruits and talk about how each looks and feels. Point out that although the fruits look different and taste different, when mixed together they make a delicious salad that everyone can enjoy. Mix all the cut fruit together in a large bowl and spoon into paper cups for individual-size servings.</p>
          <p class="footer_nav"><a href="#TOP">top of page</a></p>
          <p class="instruct_normal"><img src="images/separator_green2.gif" alt="separator" height="33" width="380" border="0"></p>
          <p class="grownups_title"><a name="FRUIT"></a><font color="#ed1c24">Friendship Fruit Freeze</font></p>
          <p class="instruct_normal">Have the children work together to prepare this tasty treat.</p>
          <p class="grownups_bold_blue">6 oz. can frozen lemonade, partially thawed<br> 6 oz. can frozen orange juice, partially thawed<br> 7 oz. can crushed pineapple, drained<br> 2 bananas, sliced<br> 2 (12 oz.) cans lemon-lime soda<br> 1/4 cup sugar</p>
          <p class="instruct_normal">Mix all the ingredients together in a 9" x 13" dish. Freeze until hard, usually overnight. Thaw slightly before serving. Cut into squares to serve.</p>
          <p class="footer_nav"><a href="#TOP">top of page</a></p>
          <p class="instruct_normal"><img src="images/separator_green2.gif" alt="separator" height="33" width="380" border="0"></p>
          <p class="grownups_title"><a name="CAKE"></a><font color="#ed1c24">Create a Fire Truck Cake</font></p>
          <p class="instruct_normal">Bake or purchase a plain loaf cake. Mix several drops of red food coloring into vanilla frosting. Cover the entire cake with the frosting. Use square cookies to represent windows on the front and sides of the cake. Add four chocolate sandwich cookies on the bottom corners to represent wheels. Add pretzel sticks for a ladder, strips of licorice for fire hoses, and a red gumdrop on the top for the siren or flashing light.</p>
          <p class="footer_nav"><a href="#TOP">top of page</a></p>
          <p class="instruct_normal"><img src="images/separator_green2.gif" alt="separator" height="33" width="380" border="0"></p>
          <p class="grownups_title"><a name="PBUTTER"></a><font color="#ed1c24">Friends are Like Peanut Butter and Jelly</font></p>
          <p class="instruct_normal">Mix peanut butter and jelly to make sandwiches. After helping stir the peanut butter and jelly together children can use blunt plastic knives to spread the mixture on bread. Remind the children that peanut butter is good all by itself and so is jelly, but together they make an especially good sandwich. Help them compare this to playing alone and playing together as friends.</p>
          <p class="footer_nav"><a href="#TOP">top of page</a></p>
          <p class="instruct_normal"><img src="images/separator_green2.gif" alt="separator" height="33" width="380" border="0"></p>
          <p class="grownups_title"><a name="SAND"></a><font color="#ed1c24">Sand Dough</font></p>
          <p class="instruct_normal">This recipe's not for eating, but it makes a great craft activity!</p>
          <p class="grownups_bold_blue">4 cups sifted sand<br> 2 cups cornstarch<br> 3 cups hot water</p>
          <p class="instruct_normal">Shake sand through a flour sifter and mix with cornstarch and hot water in an old pot. Cook over low heat, stirring with a wooden spoon. When the mixture forms a dough that pulls away from the sides of the pot, spoon it out onto wax paper and let cool. Knead well and store in a tightly covered container. Cover the work area with wax paper and have the children pat out the sand dough. Use star-shaped cookie cutters to make sea stars. Allow to air dry in the sun until hardened.</p>
